shared_text:
EDUTOPIA.ORG
Making STEM More Engaging and Inclusive

Open Way Learning
August 10 at 11:10 AM ¬∑

How can we make #STEM education more inclusive, even in the midst of a pandemic? This Edutopia article from Ben Owens & Chris Anderson provides examples of how schools are using #StudentAgency and a "context over content" approach to restore joy & wonder to STEM instruction:

https://www.edutopia.org/article/making-stem-more-engaging-and-inclusive

"The good news is that there are countless educators who are making a commitment to a more engaging approach by adopting context over content and restoring joy and wonder to STEM. This, in our view, is the way that true STEM teaching and learning should happen‚Äîand, not surprisingly, it starts by building a strong relationship with every student."

#Education #COVIDedu

post_text: My name is Lauren Kelaher. I am a teacher who just joined the TLC family from West Palm Beach, Florida! I moved to Blairsville, Georgia to raise my adorable almost 1 year old ‚ÄúJackson‚Äù with my husband John. I have been a teacher for 6 years, and am about to start my 7th year! I have mostly taught 2nd grade; which happens to be my Favorite grade to teach! I enjoy learning from my students as much as I love teaching them! I have an art background, so I always try to incorporate fun and artsy activities into my lessons. I come from a STEM school, so I also like to incorporate project based learning activities into the curriculum. I live a healthy and active lifestyle so I encourage my students to do the same. Some fun facts about me; I have a 11 month old boy named Jackson, I have two cats and a dog, I love owls, and my favorite color is teal. I am looking forward to a Wonderful year at The Learning Center!

My name is Louise Smith. I am a transplant from South Florida where I was born and raised. I was teaching in Broward County where I taught K-2 over the past 29 years. I am so excited to continue my teaching career here in North Carolina and especially to be part of the awesome TLC family.

We are about to embark on a fantastic journey. I value your involvement in your child's education. I can't wait to meet my class of Kindergarten students and their families. I'm looking forward to a year filled with lots of fun, laughter and learning.

post_text: Today‚Äôs focus for Teacher Appreciation goes out to our fantastic Nutrition Staff, Ms. Hilary, Ms. Robyn, Ms. Cindy, and Mr. Chad., and our awesome Montessori Preschool team Ms. Shirley, Ms. Tammy, Ms. Alexis, and Ms. Kristen. We are so blessed to have such a caring, supportive and entertaining nutrition staff. These team members go above and beyond in their jobs EVERY DAY, dressing up both the cafeteria and themselves for festive events, and they work to get our students involved in the events of the day also. Currently, they are working diligently to clean and sanitize the classrooms after they are used by the teachers. They rock! Now for our preschool staff: these talented young ladies have such wonderful jobs! They provide such a nurturing, supportive, and fun environment for our youngest learners. Many days you can witness our teachers singing and dancing right along with our preschoolers, which makes for a magical learning experience. It takes a special person to be a preschool teacher, and we have the cream of the crop!

post_text: Today for Teacher Appreciation, we would like to give a heartfelt shout-out to our elementary teachers, Ms. Stephanie W., Ms. Tina, Ms. Katie, Ms. Martha, Ms. Stephanie, H., Ms. Kathleen, Ms. Carrie, Ms. Emily, and Ms. Gina! The elementary years of education are so important to a child; students begin creating relationships with people outside their families in addition to transitioning into the schooling environment, and our elementary teachers must be the perfect combination of nurturing, caring, and loving to these students while they begin to make those big steps. Our elementary teachers are perfect role models for our students as they begin their educational journey. These extraordinary teachers work hard encouraging students to find their passions, supporting them through the easy and rough times, helping prepare them to advance to the middle school, and they do this gracefully while exuding warmth in all they do. We love our Elementary teachers!

post_text:
Good evening TLC families. This evening Governor Cooper just released a stay at home order, effective Monday, March 30 at 5:00 PM. As a result, our drop-off and pick up times for Monday, March 30 will be 7:30-9:30 AM, and 2:30-4:30 PM, which will allow all parents and staff to be home by 5:00. Students will be given two weeks worth of work, so no one will need to go out during this time. If you need more information on this, please contact your teachers for guidance.

I also want to assure you that during these chaotic and stressful times that TLC is here for you. The Learning Center is an essential business, so we will still be able to offer services to you as they come up. We will be communicating with you regularly about our status and what offerings we can, and continue to provide for our families. Thanks for your patience, understanding, and support during these challenging times.
text:
Good evening TLC families. This evening Governor Cooper just released a stay at home order, effective Monday, March 30 at 5:00 PM. As a result, our drop-off and pick up times for Monday, March 30 will be 7:30-9:30 AM, and 2:30-4:30 PM, which will allow all parents and staff to be home by 5:00. Students will be given two weeks worth of work, so no one will need to go out during this time. If you need more information on this, please contact your teachers for guidance.

I also want to assure you that during these chaotic and stressful times that TLC is here for you. The Learning Center is an essential business, so we will still be able to offer services to you as they come up. We will be communicating with you regularly about our status and what offerings we can, and continue to provide for our families. Thanks for your patience, understanding, and support during these challenging times.

The Cable Company, in support of Cherokee County students, announces that it has established free WIFI internet hot spots. These hot spots are open to all students, and are located at:

post_text: TLC Families - If you are in need of meals for your children during these mandated school closures, please be advised that you are invited and welcome by Cherokee County Schools to pick up meals as indicated below. Cherokee County Schools Superintendent Dr. Conley has spoken to our Head of School, Mr. Ryan Bender, and has extended this to include our school families. Thank you @cherokeecountyschoolnc .
shared_text:
Cherokee County Schools NC
March 15 at 9:06 PM ¬∑

Attention Cherokee County Families: Tomorrow March 16th we will begin allowing meal pick up at six of our schools. These are Andrews Elementary, Peachtree Elementary, Martins Creek Elementary Middle, Murphy Elementary, Hiwassee Dam School, and Ranger Elementary Middle. Parents and students can pick up the meals (2 at once a breakfast and a lunch for later) between 8am and 1pm. If you need food delivered to your child please call their school or call central office 837-2722 and give Kristie or Cindy your name, address, and numbers of students in your care. The students do not need to be with you to pick up the meals. All school aged students are eligible for free. We are also in the process of working to roll out child care assistance for families who have no alternatives and need to work. Please tell our students that their teachers and principals love them and miss them and will see them again soon. Thank you all for your support during this mandated closure.
